      textEn: [
        "It was the custom in our town of Lu Zhen that married daughters, if they were not yet the heads of their households, would mostly go back to their mothers\u2019 homes for the summer. My grandmother was still healthy then, but my mother had already taken on some household duties, so summer visits had to be short. She could only spare a few days after the tomb-sweeping was done, and every year I would follow her to stay at my maternal grandmother\u2019s house. The place was called Pingqiao Village \u2014 a remote little riverside hamlet not far from the sea.",
        "My playmates were many young friends, who, because a guest had come from afar, had all gotten permission from their parents to reduce their work and keep me company in games.",
        "Our daily activities mainly consisted of digging for earthworms, threading them on copper-wire hooks, and lying by the riverbank to fish for shrimp.",
        "What I most looked forward to there was going to Zhao Village to watch the opera.",
        "It was in the year when I was eleven or twelve that this date finally arrived. Unfortunately, that year no boat could be found in the morning.",
        "Grandmother and Mother believed them and stopped objecting, smiling. We dashed out the door in a rush.",
        "The fragrance of beans and wheat on both banks and water-plants on the riverbed drifted toward us mixed in the mist. Moonlight was hazy in this mist. The dark undulating mountains seemed like the leaping iron spines of beasts, all running away toward the stern.",
        "Most eye-catching was the opera stage standing on open ground by the river outside the village, hazy in the distant moonlight, almost merging with the sky \u2014 I suspected the fairyland I had seen in paintings had appeared right here.",
        "The moon had not yet set. Leaving Zhao Village, the moonlight seemed even brighter. Looking back at the stage in the lamplight, it once again looked misty like a fairy mountain pavilion.",
        "About a mile from Pingqiao Village the boat slowed. The rowers said they were exhausted. It was Guisheng who came up with the idea: the broad beans were at their peak and firewood was ready \u2014 we could steal some to cook.",
        "Truly, to this day I have never again tasted beans as good as those that night \u2014 nor seen opera as good as that night\u2019s."
      ],
